{"title_page": "Reed Smoot (cinematographer)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=January 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Reed Smoot\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[United States]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| parents =\n| spouse =\n| occupation = [[Cinematographer]]\n| yearsactive =\n}}\n'''Reed P. Smoot''' [[American Society of Cinematographers|A.S.C.]] is a [[United States]] [[cinematography|cinematographer]] associated with many successful [[IMAX]] [[Documentary film|documentaries]] and theme park rides.\nHe also did the cinematography for ''[[The Great American Cowboy]]'', which won the 1973 [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for best documentary feature.\n\nSmoot is a [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|Latter-day Saint]].<ref>[http://ldsfilm.com/box/2002/2002_09_06.html LDS Films Weekend Box Office Report 6 September 2002<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He received a BA in Advertising from [[BYU]] in 1969, and is married to his wife Julia.<ref>[http://www.byhigh.org/Alumni_P_to_T/Smoot/ReedP.html Byhigh.org]</ref>\n\n==Cinematography==\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''[[Are You Listening? (1971 film)|Are You Listening?]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[The Great American Cowboy]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[The Lost Manuscript]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Cipher in the Snow]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[The First Vision (1976 film)|The First Vision]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[John Baker's Last Race]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[The Phone Call (1977 film)|The Phone Call]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Mailbox (film)|The Mailbox]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Gift (1977 film)|The Gift]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Where Jesus Walked]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Uncle Ben (1978 film)|Uncle Ben]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Great Brain (1978 film)|The Great Brain]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Emmett Smith Story]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Take Down (1979 film)|Take Down]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[The Trophy Case]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[In One Blinding Moment]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Windwalk